# Contributing to HARPER

Thank you for your interest in the HARPER Project. Contributions are welcome and appreciated, whether you want to fix a bug, improve documentation, add hardware designs, or extend the ROS 2 stack, issues and pull requests are encouraged.

HARPER is an open-source hardware and software effort from the Interdisciplinary Robotics Research Lab (IRRL) and the Cognitive Science Department at Vassar College. Many packages in this repository are still work in progress, so help in any area is valuable.

## Ways to contribute

You do not need to write code to contribute. Useful contributions include:

- Bug reports with clear steps to reproduce
- Documentation fixes, tutorials, and README improvements
- URDF/mesh updates, 3D print files, mechanical design feedback

## How to contribute

### 1. Open an issue (recommended for larger changes)

For substantial features or design changes, open an issue first so we can align on approach before you invest significant time. Small fixes (typos, obvious bugs) can go straight to a pull request.

### 2. Fork and branch

1. Fork [github.com/Vassar-IRRL/harper](https://github.com/Vassar-IRRL/harper)
2. Clone your fork and create a branch from `main`
3. Use a descriptive branch name (e.g. `fix/urdf-mesh-path`, `docs/contributing-guide`)

### 3. Make your changes

- Keep each pull request focused on one logical change when possible
- Match existing style and conventions in the package you are editing
- Update the relevant package README if you change behavior, APIs, or setup steps
- For ROS 2 packages, build and test locally before opening a PR

